    "# 🧭 Syndicate 3.0: Phase 4 Playroom (High-Dimensional Geometry)\n",
    "\n",
    "In semantic search, text documents are represented as high-dimensional **embeddings** (vectors in space). To query them, we must measure the distance or similarity between these vectors.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this playroom, you will discover the **document length bias** that ruins Euclidean distance metrics, and learn the linear algebra behind **Cosine Similarity** to navigate high-dimensional latent spaces using pure Python primitives.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 📐 4.1: The Limits of Euclidean Distance\n",
    "\n",
    "### 🧪 Discovery Lab: The Attack of Document Length Bias\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have a user's search query vector:\n",
    "$$\\mathbf{Q} = [1.0, 0.0]$$\n",
    "(representing \"pure software coding\").\n",
    "\n",
    "We have two documents in our database:\n",
    "- **Doc A:** $\\mathbf{A} = [4.0, 0.0]$ (purely about software coding, but a very long text with many word occurrences).\n",
    "- **Doc B:** $\\mathbf{B} = [1.0, 1.0]$ (shorter, but splits attention equally between coding and recipes).\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. The Naive Attempt (Euclidean Distance)\n",
    "Let's measure the straight-line (Euclidean) distance between the query and both documents using the Pythagorean Theorem."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import math\n",
    "\n",
    "q = [1.0, 0.0]\n",
    "doc_a = [4.0, 0.0]\n",
    "doc_b = [1.0, 1.0]\n",
    "\n",
    "dist_q_a = math.sqrt((doc_a[0] - q[0])**2 + (doc_a[1] - q[1])**2)\n",
    "dist_q_b = math.sqrt((doc_b[0] - q[0])**2 + (doc_b[1] - q[1])**2)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Distance to Doc A (pure coding): {dist_q_a:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Distance to Doc B (mixed content): {dist_q_b:.4f}\")\n",
    "# Look at the output. Why is Doc B mathematically closer to the query than Doc A, even though Doc A has 100% overlap in semantic direction?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 2. The Mathematical Necessity\n",
    "Euclidean distance measures the length of the vector difference. It is heavily biased by **vector magnitude (document length)**. A very long document in the same semantic direction will have larger values, pushing it far away in Euclidean space.\n",
    "\n",
    "We must ignore the *length* of the vectors and measure only the **angle $\\theta$ between their directions**. When the angle is $0^\\circ$ (Cosine of $\\theta = 1.0$), the semantic directions are perfectly aligned.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. The Rosetta Stone (Cosine Similarity Equation)\n",
    "$$\\text{Similarity}(\\mathbf{u}, \\mathbf{v}) = \\cos(\\theta) = \\frac{\\mathbf{u} \\cdot \\mathbf{v}}{\\|\\mathbf{u}\\| \\|\\mathbf{v}\\|} = \\frac{\\sum u_i v_i}{\\sqrt{\\sum u_i^2} \\sqrt{\\sum v_i^2}}$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
